scussions in France and Sweden about the Genocide of 1915 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe mass killing of Ottoman Armenians is today widely recognized, both within and outside scholarly circles, as an act of genocide. What is less well known, however, is that it took place within a broader context of Ottoman violence against minority groups during and after the First World War. Among those populations decimated were the indigenous Christian Assyrians (also known as Syriacs or Chaldeans) who lived in the borderlands of present-day Turkey, Iran, and Iraq. This volume is the first scholarly edited collection focused on the Assyrian genocide, or “Sayfo” (literally, “sword” in Aramaic), presenting historical, psychological, anthropological, and political perspectives that shed much-needed light on a neglected historical atrocity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAssyriansxHistoryx20th centuryxIran. 0aAssyriansxHistoryx20th centuryxIraq. 0aAssyriansxHistoryx20th centuryxTurkey. 0aAssyrianszIranxHistoryy20th century. 0aAssyrianszIraqxHistoryy20th century. 0aAssyrianszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aChaldean CatholicsxHistoryx20th century. 0aChaldean CatholicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aGenocidexReligious aspectsxHistoryx20th century. 0aGenocidexReligious aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMassacresxHistoryx20th centuryxIran. 0aMassacresxHistoryx20th centuryxIraq. 0aMassacresxHistoryx20th centuryxTurkey. 0aMassacreszIranxHistoryy20th century. 0aMassacreszIraqxHistoryy20th century. 0aMassacreszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryx20th centuryxIran. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryx20th centuryxIraq. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryx20th centuryxTur